  "text": "Kubernetes enforces RBAC privilege escalation prevention through a multi-layer validation architecture. The core escalation validation is implemented in pkg/registry/rbac/escalation_check.go with three critical functions: EscalationAllowed() checks if a user is in the system:masters privileged group, RoleEscalationAuthorized() checks if a user has explicit 'escalate' verb authorization on clusterroles/roles, and BindingAuthorized() checks if a user has 'bind' verb authorization to prevent binding roles they don't hold. These functions are invoked during Create and Update operations by policy-based storage handlers in pkg/registry/rbac/{clusterrole,clusterrolebinding,role,rolebinding}/policybased/storage.go. The validation logic centers around ConfirmNoEscalation() in pkg/registry/rbac/validation/rule.go, which uses the Covers() function from staging/src/k8s.io/component-helpers/auth/rbac/validation/policy_comparator.go to verify that a user's existing permissions fully cover any new permissions they attempt to grant. The Covers() function breaks down rules into atomic tuples and uses ruleCovers() to ensure ownership. CompactRules() in policy_compact.go optimizes error messages by consolidating similar rules. The DefaultRuleResolver in validation/rule.go aggregates all applicable rules for a user by consulting ClusterRoleBindings and RoleBindings. The RBACAuthorizer plugin in plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/rbac.go evaluates requests against these rules using RuleAllows(), which matches verbs, API groups, resources, and resource names. Helper functions in pkg/apis/rbac/helpers.go and evaluation_helpers.go provide rule matching utilities. This architecture prevents privilege escalation by ensuring users can only grant permissions they already possess, blocking users from binding roles with permissions they lack, and restricting special verbs like 'escalate' and 'bind' to authorized administrators."
}

